  "prompt": "What is frictional force?",
  "response": "Frictional force is the resistance to motion that occurs when two surfaces are in contact with each other. It acts in the opposite direction to the motion of the object or attempted motion of the object. There are several types of frictional forces, including:\n\n1. **Static Friction**: This type of friction resists the initiation of motion between two surfaces that are in contact and at rest relative to one another. It needs to be overcome to start moving an object.\n\n2. **Kinetic (or Sliding) Friction**: This occurs when two surfaces are moving relative to each other. It is usually less than static friction, which is why objects tend to keep moving once they\u2019ve started.\n\n3. **Rolling Friction**: This type of friction occurs when an object rolls over a surface. Rolling friction is generally less than sliding friction, which is why wheels and ball bearings are effective in reducing resistance.\n\n4. **Fluid Friction**: This type is experienced by objects moving through a fluid (liquid or gas). It is also known as drag, and it depends on the object's speed, its shape, and the fluid's properties.\n\nFrictional forces play a crucial role in everyday life, providing the grip needed for walking, driving, and holding objects. However, they also cause wear and tear on moving parts and can be undesirable in mechanical systems where efficiency is needed.",
